"Li G., Ren B., Yang C., Zheng J.","Revisiting the trend of the tropical and subtropical Pacific surface latent heat flux during 1977-2006",2011,"Journal of Geophysical Research Atmospheres","116","10", D10115,"","",,,10.1029/2010JD015444,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79958065285&partnerID=40&md5=eeb11793d8dec88e354a8981a5aabe92","School of Earth and Space Sciences, University of Science and Technology of China, 96 JinZhai Rd., Hefei, Anhui 230026, China","Li, G., School of Earth and Space Sciences, University of Science and Technology of China, 96 JinZhai Rd., Hefei, Anhui 230026, China; Ren, B., School of Earth and Space Sciences, University of Science and Technology of China, 96 JinZhai Rd., Hefei, Anhui 230026, China; Yang, C., School of Earth and Space Sciences, University of Science and Technology of China, 96 JinZhai Rd., Hefei, Anhui 230026, China; Zheng, J., School of Earth and Space Sciences, University of Science and Technology of China, 96 JinZhai Rd., Hefei, Anhui 230026, China","Using the Objectively Analyzed Air-Sea Fluxes data provided by the Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution and the trend empirical orthogonal function analysis method, we have investigated the trend of ocean surface latent heat flux (LHF) over the tropical and subtropical Pacific (100°E-70°W, 35°S-35°N) during the period 1977-2006. The present study suggests that the ocean surface LHF presents a large-scale upward trend pattern, and the identified positive surface LHF trend is closely associated with both the sea surface temperature (SST) warming and the surface wind speed strengthening. The SST increasing is the primary direct/local cause of the surface LHF trend, while the large-scale surface wind speed strengthening, ascribed to its contribution to the observed SST trend pattern, is an important indirect/nonlocal factor of the surface LHF trend. The present work also suggests that the coherent upward trends in surface LHF, surface wind speed, and SST should be in essence closely linked to the global warming forcing. To some extent, these results unify the two seemingly contradictory conclusions proposed previously by other researchers and attempt to help obtain a new insight into the causes of the positive basin-scale surface LHF trend. Copyright 2011 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Atmospheric temperature; Fourier analysis; Global warming; Latent heat; Orthogonal functions; Strengthening (metal); Surface waters; Tropics; Wind effects; Air sea flux; Empirical orthogonal function analysis; Ocean surfaces; Sea surface temperatures; Surface latent heat fluxes; Surface wind speed; Upward trend; Woods hole oceanographic institutions; Heat flux; climate forcing; data set; global warming; latent heat flux; marine atmosphere; reconstruction; sea surface temperature; surface flux; temporal analysis; trend analysis; warming; wind velocity; Pacific Ocean; Pacific Ocean (Subtropical); Pacific Ocean (Tropical)",,,,,,"Alexander, M.A., Scott, J.D., Surface flux variability over the north pacific and north atlantic oceans (1997) J. Clim., 10, pp. 2963-2978. , doi:10.1175/1520-0442(1997)010<2963:SFVOTN>2.0.CO;2; An, S.-I., Conditional maximum covariance analysis and its application to the Tropical Indian Ocean SST and surface wind stress anomalies (2003) Journal of Climate, 16 (17), pp. 2932-2938. , DOI 10.1175/1520-0442(2003)016<2932:CMCAAI>2.0.CO;2; Araligidad, N.M., Maloney, E.D., Wind-driven latent heat flux and the intraseasonal oscillation (2008) Geophysical Research Letters, 35 (4), pp. L04815. , DOI 10.1029/2007GL032746; Barbosa, S.M., Andersen, O.B., Trend patterns in global sea surface temperature (2009) Int. J. Climatol., 29, pp. 2049-2055. , doi:10.1002/joc.1855; Behera, S.K., Salvekar, P.S., Yamagata, T., Simulation of inter-annual SST variability in the tropical Indian Ocean (2000) J. Clim., 13, pp. 3487-3499. , doi:10.1175/1520-0442(2000)013<3487:SOISVI>2.0.CO;2; Bjerknes, J., Atmospheric teleconnections from the equatorial pacific (1969) Mon. Weather Rev., 97, pp. 163-172. , doi:10.1175/1520-0493(1969)097<0163:ATFTEP>2.3.CO;2; Cane, M.A., Clement, A.C., Kaplan, A., Kushnir, Y., Pozdnyakov, D., Seager, R., Zebiak, S.E., Murtugudde, R., Twentieth-century sea surface temperature trends (1997) Science, 275 (5302), pp. 957-960. , DOI 10.1126/science.275.5302.957; Cayan, D.R., Variability of latent and sensible heat fluxes estimated using bulk formulae (1992) Atmos. Ocean, 30, pp. 1-42; Cayan, D.R., Latent and sensible heat flux Anomalies over the northern oceans: The connection to monthly atmospheric circulation (1992) J. Clim., 5, pp. 354-369. , doi:10.1175/1520-0442(1992)005<0354:LASHFA>2.0.CO;2; Cayan, D.R., Latent and sensible heat flux Anomalies over the northern oceans: Driving the sea surface temperature (1992) J. Phys. Oceanogr., 22, pp. 859-881. , doi:10.1175/1520-0485(1992)022<0859:LASHFA>2.0.CO;2; Cess, R.D., Udelhofen, P.M., Climate change during 1985-1999: Cloud interactions determined from satellite measurements (2003) Geophys. Res. Lett., 30 (1), p. 1019. , doi:10.1029/2002GL016128; Chen, J., Carlson, B.E., Del Genio, A.D., Evidence for strengthening of the tropical general circulation in the 1990s (2002) Science, 295 (5556), pp. 838-841. , DOI 10.1126/science.1065835; Clement, A.C., Seager, R., Cane, M.A., Zebiak, S.E., An ocean dynamical thermostat (1996) J. Clim., 9, pp. 2190-2196. , doi:10.1175/1520-0442(1996)009<2190:AODT>2.0.CO;2; Da Silva, A.M., Levitus, S., (1994) Anomalies of Heat and Momentum Fluxes, 3, p. 413. , Atlas of Surface Marine Data 1994 U.S. Dep. of Comm., Washington, D. C; Fairall, C.W., Bradley, E.F., Hare, J.E., Grachev, A.A., Edson, J.B., Bulk parameterization of air-sea fluxes: Updates and verification for the COARE algorithm (2003) Journal of Climate, 16 (4), pp. 571-591; Fang, C., Wu, L., The role of ocean dynamics in tropical pacific SST response to warm climate in a fully coupled GCM (2008) Geophys. Res. Lett., 35, pp. L08703. , doi:1